# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: place-and-route
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] In electronic design automation, a **floorplan** of an integrated circuit consists of a schematic arrangement of its major functional blocks on the chip area and the specification of high-level parameters such as the **aspect ratio** or **core utilization**.
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] The design step in which floorplans are created is called **floorplanning**, an early stage in the design flow for integrated circuit design.
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] Various mathematical abstractions of this problem have been studied.
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] The floorplanning design stage consists of various steps with the aim of finding floorplans that allow a timing-clean routing and spread power consumption over the whole chip.
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] In mathematics floorplanning refers to the problem of packing smaller rectangles with a fixed or unfixed orientation into a larger rectangle.
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] The dimensions of the larger and smaller rectangles might be fixed (hard constraints) or must be optimized (soft constraints).
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] Additionally, a measure modelling the quality of routing that the floorplan allows might be optimized.
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] Various variants of rectangle packing are NP-hard.
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] A sliceable floorplan is a floorplan that may be defined recursively as described below.
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] The process is known as guillotine cutting.
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] Sliceable floorplans have been used in a number of early electronic design automation tools for a number of reasons.
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] Sliceable floorplans may be conveniently represented by binary trees (more specifically, *k*-d trees), which correspond to the order of slicing.
[src:place-and-route/floorplan-microelectronics] More importantly, a number of NP-hard problems with floorplans have polynomial time algorithms when restricted to sliceable floorplans.
[src:place-and-route/lef-def] The DEF file contains all information related to the particular electronic circuit design: design constraints, layout, netlist.
[src:place-and-route/lef-def] The LEF file contains library information related to cells and modules used in the design, as well as information about layers, vias, P&R boundary and some other information useful for P&R.
[src:place-and-route/lef-def] LEF and DEF were developed at Tangent Systems by Aki Fujimura for their place and route tools, which were bought by Cadence in 1989.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] In electronic design, a **netlist** is a description of the connectivity of an electronic circuit.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] In its simplest form, a netlist consists of a list of the electronic components in a circuit and a list of the nodes they are connected to.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] A network (net) is a collection of two or more interconnected components.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] The structure, complexity and representation of netlists can vary considerably, but the fundamental purpose of every netlist is to convey connectivity information.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Netlists usually provide nothing more than instances, nodes, and perhaps some attributes of the components involved.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] If they express much more than this, they are usually considered to be a hardware description language such as Verilog or VHDL, or one of several languages specifically designed for input to simulators or hardware compilers (such as SPICE analog simulation netlists).
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Most netlists either contain or refer to descriptions of the parts or devices used.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Each time a part is used in a netlist, this is called an "instance".
[src:place-and-route/netlist] These descriptions will usually list the connections that are made to that kind of device, and some basic properties of that device.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] These connection points are called "terminals" or "pins", among several other names.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] An "instance" could be anything from a MOSFET transistor or a bipolar junction transistor, to a resistor, a capacitor, or an integrated circuit chip.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] In the case of a vacuum cleaner, these terminals would be the three metal prongs in the plug.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Each terminal has a name, and in continuing the vacuum cleaner example, they might be "Neutral", "Live" and "Ground".
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Usually, each instance will have a unique name, so that if you have two instances of vacuum cleaners, one might be "vac1" and the other "vac2".
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Besides their names, they might otherwise be identical.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Networks (nets) are the "wires" that connect things together in the circuit.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] There may or may not be any special attributes associated with the nets in a design, depending on the particular language the netlist is written in, and that language's features.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Instance based netlists usually provide a list of the instances used in a design.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Along with each instance, either an ordered list of net names is provided, or a list of pairs provided, of an instance port name, along with the net name to which that port is connected.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] In this kind of description, the list of nets can be gathered from the connection lists, and there is no place to associate particular attributes with the nets themselves.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] SPICE is an example of instance-based netlists.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Net-based netlists usually describe all the instances and their attributes, then describe each net, and say which port they are connected on each instance.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] This allows for attributes to be associated with nets.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] EDIF is probably the most famous of the net-based netlists.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] In large designs, it is a common practice to split the design into pieces, each piece becoming a "definition" which can be used as instances in the design.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] In the vacuum cleaner analogy, one might have a vacuum cleaner definition with its ports, but now this definition would also include a full description of the machine's internal components and how they connect (motors, switches, etc.), like a wiring diagram does.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] A definition which includes no instances is called a "primitive" (or a "leaf", or other names); whereas a definition which includes instances is "hierarchical".
[src:place-and-route/netlist] A "folded" hierarchy allows a single definition to be represented several times by instances.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] An "unfolded" hierarchy does not allow a definition to be used more than once in the hierarchy.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Folded hierarchies can be extremely compact.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] A small netlist of just a few instances can describe designs with a very large number of instances.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] For example, suppose definition A is a simple primitive, like a memory cell.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Then suppose definition B contains 32 instances of A; C contains 32 instances of B; D contains 32 instances of C; and E contains 32 instances of D.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] The design now contains 5 definitions (A through E) and 128 instances.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Yet, E describes a circuit that contains over a million memory cells.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] In a "flat" design, only primitives are instanced.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Hierarchical designs can be recursively "exploded" ("flattened") by creating a new copy (with a new name) of each definition each time it is used.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] If the design is highly folded, expanding it like this will result in a much larger netlist database, but preserves the hierarchy dependencies.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Given a hierarchical netlist, the list of instance names in a path from the root definition to a primitive instance specifies the single unique path to that primitive.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] The paths to every primitive, taken together, comprise a large but flat netlist that is exactly equivalent to the compact hierarchical version.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Backannotation is data that could be added to a hierarchical netlist.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Usually they are kept separate from the netlist, because several such alternate sets of data could be applied to a single netlist.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] These data may have been extracted from a physical design, and might provide extra information for more accurate simulations.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Usually the data are composed of a hierarchical path and a piece of data for that primitive or finding the values of RC delay due to interconnection.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Another concept often used in netlists is that of inheritance.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Suppose a definition of a capacitor has an associated attribute called "Capacitance", corresponding to the physical property of the same name, with a default value of "100 pF" (100 picofarads).
[src:place-and-route/netlist] Each instance of this capacitor might also have such an attribute, only with a different value of capacitance.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] And other instances might not associate any capacitance at all.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] In the case where no capacitance is specified for an instance, the instance will "inherit" the 100 pF value from its definition.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] A value specified will "override" the value on the definition.
[src:place-and-route/netlist] If a great number of attributes end up being the same as on the definition, a great amount of information can be "inherited", and not have to be redundantly specified in the netlist, saving space, and making the design easier to read by both machines and people.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] These processes are similar at a high level, but the actual details are very different.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] With the large sizes of modern designs, this operation is usually performed by electronic design automation (EDA) tools.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] In all these contexts, the final result when placing and routing is finished is the "layout", a geometric description of the location and rotation of each part, and the exact path of each wire connecting them.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] Occasionally some people call the entire place-and-route process "layout".
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] The design of a printed circuit board comes after the creation of a schematic and generation of a netlist.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] The generated netlist is then read into a layout tool and associated with the footprints of the devices from a library.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] Placing and routing the devices can now start.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] Placing and routing is generally done in two steps.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] Placing the components comes first, then routing the connections between the components.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] The placement of components is not absolute during the routing phase, as it may still be changed by moving and rotating, especially with designs using more complex components such as FPGAs or microprocessors.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] Their large number of signals, and their signal integrity needs may require optimization of the placement.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] The resulting design is then output in RS-274X Gerber format to load in the computer-aided manufacturing (CAM) system of the manufacturer.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] In contrast to an IC layout, where the entire finished layout is stored in one graphics file, different files and formats are needed for PCB manufacture.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] The fabrication data consists of a set of Gerber files, a drill file, and a pick-and-place file containing the location and alignment of the devices generated for automated placement of the devices in the assembly process.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] The process of placing and routing for an FPGA is generally not performed by a person, but uses a tool provided by the FPGA Vendor or another software manufacturer.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] The need for software tools is because of the complexity of the circuitry within the FPGA and the function the designer wishes to perform.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] FPGA designs are described using logic diagrams containing digital logic and hardware description languages such as VHDL and Verilog.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] These will then be put through an automated place-and-route procedure to generate a pinout, which will be used to interface with the parts outside of the FPGA.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] The IC place-and-route stage typically starts with one or more schematics, HDL files, or pre-routed IP cores, or some combination of all three.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] It produces an IC layout that is automatically converted to a mask work in the standard GDS II or the OASIS format.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] The final layout of early ICs and PCBs was stored as a tape-out of Rubylith on transparent film.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] Gradually, electronic design automation automated more and more of the place-and-route work.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] At first, it merely sped up the process of making many small edits without spending a lot of time peeling up and sticking down the tape.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] Later design rule checking sped up the process of checking for the most common sorts of errors.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] Later auto routers speed up the process of routing.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] Some people hope that further improvements in autoplacers and autorouters will eventually produce good layouts without any human manual intervention.
[src:place-and-route/place-and-route] Further automation leads to the idea of a silicon compiler.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] A placer takes a given synthesized circuit netlist together with a technology library and produces a valid placement layout.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] The layout is optimized according to the aforementioned objectives and ready for cell resizing and buffering — a step essential for timing and signal integrity satisfaction.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Clock tree synthesis and Routing follow, completing the physical design process.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] In many cases, parts of, or the entire, physical design flow are iterated a number of times until design closure is achieved.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] In the case of application-specific integrated circuits, or ASICs, the chip's core layout area comprises a number of fixed height rows, with either some or no space between them.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Each row consists of a number of sites which can be occupied by the circuit components.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] A free site is a site that is not occupied by any component.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Circuit components are either standard cells, macro blocks, or I/O pads.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Standard cells have a fixed height equal to a row's height, but have variable widths.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] The width of a cell is an integral number of sites.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] On the other hand, blocks are typically larger than cells and have variable heights that can stretch a multiple number of rows.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Some blocks can have preassigned locations — say from a previous floorplanning process — which limit the placer's task to assigning locations for just the cells.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] In this case, the blocks are typically referred to by fixed blocks.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Alternatively, some or all of the blocks may not have preassigned locations.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] In this case, they have to be placed with the cells in what is commonly referred to as mixed-mode placement.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] In addition to ASICs, placement retains its prime importance in gate array structures such as field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs).
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Here, prefabricated transistors are typically arranged in rows (or “arrays”) that are separated by routing channels.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Placement maps the circuit's subcircuits into programmable FPGA logic blocks in a manner that guarantees the completion of the subsequent stage of routing.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Placement is formulated as **constrained optimization**.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] In particular, the clock cycle of a chip is determined by the delay of its longest path, usually referred to as the critical path.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Given a performance specification, a placer must ensure that no path exists with delay exceeding the maximum specified delay.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Additionally, it is desirable to finish the placement process quickly.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Total wirelength is typically the primary objective of most existing placers and serves as a precursor to other optimizations because, e.g., power and delay tend to grow with wire length.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Total wire length determines the routing demand and whether it can be satisfied by the routing supply defined by available routing tracks.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] However, making wires very short sometimes leads to local routing demand exceeding local routing supply.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Such situations often require routing detours, which increase wire lengths and signal delays.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Therefore, after preliminary optimization of total wirelength, it is also important to handle routing congestion.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Power minimization typically notes wires with greater switching activity factors and assigns greater priority to making them shorter.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] When many "hot" components are placed nearby, a hot spot may arise and lead to harmful temperature gradients.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] In such cases, components can be spread out.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Placement is divided into global placement and detailed placement.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Global placement introduces dramatic changes by distributing all the instances to appropriate locations in a global scale with minor overlaps allowed.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Detailed placement shifts each instance to nearby legal location with very moderate layout change.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Placement and overall design quality is most dependent on the global placement performance.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Early techniques for placement of integrated circuits can be categorized as combinatorial optimization.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] For IC designs with thousands or tens of thousands of components, **simulated annealing** methodologies such as TimberWolf exhibits the best results.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] When IC designs grew to millions of components, placement leveraged **hypergraph partitioning** using nested-partitioning frameworks such as Capo.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Combinatorial methods directly prevent component overlaps but struggle with interconnect optimization at large scale.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] They are typically stochastic and can produce very different results for the same input when launched multiple times.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Analytical methods for global placement model interconnect length by a continuous function and minimize this function directly subject to component density constraints.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] These methods run faster and scale better than combinatorial methods, but do not prevent component overlaps and must be postprocessed by combinatorial methods for detailed placement.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] **Quadratic placement** is an early analytical method that models interconnect length by a quadratic function and uses high-performance quadratic optimization techniques.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] When it was developed, it demonstrated competitive quality of results and also stability, unlike combinatorial methods.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] GORDIAN formulates the wirelength cost as a quadratic function while still spreading cells apart through recursive partitioning.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] The algorithm models placement density as a linear term into the quadratic cost function and solves the placement problem by pure quadratic programming.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] A common enhancement is weighting each net by the inverse of its length on the previous iteration.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] Provided the process converges, this minimizes an objective **linear** in the wirelength.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] The majority of modern quadratic placers (KraftWerk, FastPlace, SimPL) follow this framework, each with different heuristics on how to determine the linear density force.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] ePlace is a state-of-the-art global placement algorithm.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] It spreads instances apart by simulating an electrostatic field, which minimizes quality overhead thus achieves good performance.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] In 2021, Google Brain reported good results from the use of AI techniques (in particular, reinforcement learning) for the placement problem.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] However, this result is quite controversial, as the paper does not contain head-to-head comparisons to existing placers, and is difficult to replicate due to proprietary content.
[src:place-and-route/placement-electronic-design-automation] At least one initially favorable commentary has been retracted upon further review.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] In electronic design, **wire routing**, commonly called simply **routing**, is a step in the design of printed circuit boards (PCBs) and integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] It builds on a preceding step, called placement, which determines the location of each active element of an IC or component on a PCB.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] After placement, the routing step adds wires needed to properly connect the placed components while obeying all design rules for the IC.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Together, the placement and routing steps of IC design are known as place and route.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] They are given some pre-existing polygons consisting of pins (also called terminals) on cells, some obstacles where wires cannot be routed, and optionally some pre-existing wiring called preroutes.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Each of the pins is associated with a net, usually by name or number.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] The primary task of the router is to create geometries such that all terminals assigned to the same net are connected, no terminals assigned to different nets are connected, and all design rules are obeyed.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] A router can fail by not connecting terminals that should be connected (an open), by mistakenly connecting two terminals that should not be connected (a short), or by creating a design rule violation.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] In addition to correctly connecting the nets, routers may also be expected to make sure the design meets timing, has no crosstalk problems, meets any metal density requirements, does not suffer from antenna effects, and so on.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] This long list of often conflicting objectives is what makes routing extremely difficult.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Almost every problem associated with routing is known to be intractable.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] The simplest routing problem, called the Steiner tree problem, of finding the shortest route for one net in one layer with no obstacles and no design rules is known to be NP-complete, both in the case where all angles are allowed or if routing is restricted to only horizontal and vertical wires.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Variants of channel routing have also been shown to be NP-complete, as well as routing which reduces crosstalk, number of vias, and so on.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Even before routing problems were proved NP-complete, the difficulty of finding optimal solutions was apparent.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Therefore almost all algorithms are based on heuristics, which do not try for an optimum, but instead a solution that is "good enough".
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Design rules sometimes vary considerably from layer to layer.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] On integrated circuits with multiple metal layers, for example, the allowed width and spacing on the lower layers may be four or more times smaller than the allowed widths and spacings on the upper layers.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] This introduces many additional complications not faced by routers for other applications such as printed circuit board or multi-chip module design.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Particular difficulties ensue if the rules are not simple multiples of each other, and when vias must traverse between layers with different rules.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] The earliest types of EDA routers were "manual routers"—the drafter clicked a mouse on the endpoint of each line segment of each net.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Modern PCB design software typically provides "interactive routers"—the drafter selects a pad and clicks a few places to give the EDA tool an idea of where to go, and the EDA tool tries to place wires as close to that path as possible without violating design rule checking (DRC).
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Some more advanced interactive routers have "push and shove" (aka "shove-aside" or "automoving") features in an interactive router; the EDA tool pushes other nets out of the way, if possible, in order to place a new wire where the drafter wants it and still avoid violating DRC.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Modern PCB design software also typically provides "autorouters" that route all remaining unrouted connections without human intervention.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Modern integrated circuits typically use fully automatic routing, as there can be far too many nets to route by hand.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] If the automatic routing does not yield a fully routed solution, a typical fix is to change the placement to allow more room for the routes, rather than try to complete the missing routes manually.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] This process repeats until all nets are routed or the program (or user) gives up.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] An alternative approach is to treat shorts, design rule violations, obstructions, etc. on a similar footing as excess wire length—that is, as finite costs to be reduced (at first) rather than as absolutes to be avoided.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Most routers assign wiring layers to carry predominantly "x" or "y" directional wiring, though there have been routers which avoid or reduce the need for such assignment.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] There are advantages and disadvantages to each approach.
[src:place-and-route/routing-electronic-design-automation] Restricted directions make power supply design and the control of inter-layer crosstalk easier, but allowing arbitrary routes can reduce the need for vias and decrease the number of required wiring layers.
